  "body": "<!-- Please use this template while reporting a bug and provide as much info as possible. Not doing so may result in your bug not being addressed in a timely manner. Thanks!\r\n\r\nIf the matter is security related, please disclose it privately via https://kubernetes.io/security/\r\n-->\r\n\r\n\r\n**What happened**:\r\nWe found that \r\n1. azure cloud provider tries to attach a disk, it totally costs 121s in the end\r\n2. after one minute(disk still in being detaching state), azure cloud provider tries to delete that disk and it succeeded\r\n3. after 121s, attach disk operation succeeded and finally azure vm has attached one **non-existing** disk\r\n\r\n**What you expected to happen**:\r\nshould not delete an azure disk when that disk is being attached\r\n\r\n**How to reproduce it (as minimally and precisely as possible)**:\r\n\r\n**Anything else we need to know?**:\r\nThe difficulty here is when a disk is being attached or detached, the disk state is still \"unattached\", would be the reason why delete disk at that time would succeed:\r\nhttps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/microsoft.azure.management.compute.models.diskstate?view=azure-dotnet\r\n\r\nAzure disk RP would have two options to fix this issue:\r\n1. provide a new disk state: `beingAttaching`, `beingDetaching`\r\n2. reject disk delete operation when disk is being attached or detached\r\n\r\nOtherwise on azure provider(client) side, we cannot know whether that disk is being attached or detached since the second delete disk operation is done after 1 min\r\n\r\n**Environment**:\r\n- Kubernetes version (use `kubectl version`):\r\n- Cloud provider or hardware configuration:\r\n- OS (e.g: `cat /etc/os-release`):\r\n- Kernel (e.g. `uname -a`):\r\n- Install tools:\r\n- Network plugin and version (if this is a network-related bug):\r\n- Others:\r\n\r\n/kind bug\r\n/assign \r\n/priority important-soon\r\n/sig cloud-provider\r\n/area provider/azure",
